92","1270":"1270","Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lynn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhloinn</b> and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn  ).","Scottish: variant of   Lyne   3.","English: habitational name from any of several places so called in Norfolk, in particular King's Lynn, an important center of the medieval wool trade. The placename is probably from an Old Welsh word cognate with Gaelic <i>linn</i> ‘pool, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Ding, Fatt, Tov, Yol, Yun.","Scottish and English: variant of   Lynn  .","Probably also an altered form of Dutch <b>Van der Lijn</b> (see   Vanderlinden  )."]},{"name":"Linn","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","German: habitational name from a place called Linn, named with <i>lin</i> ‘swamp, bog, marsh’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Linto</i>, formed with Old High German <i>lind(i)</i> ‘soft’."]},{"name":"Lenn","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","Jewish(Ashkenazic): variant of   Len  ."]},{"name":"Flynn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Connor, Declan, Kieran, Aidan, Brigid, Cathal, Dermot, Donal, Eamon, John Patrick, Kiernan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Floinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Flann</i>’, a byname meaning ‘red(dish), ruddy’. There were families of this name in various parts of Ireland. This name has also been Anglicized as   Lindsay  .","English: from Middle English <i>Flin</i>, representing the Old Norse male personal name <i>Fleinn</i>."]},{"name":"Lynne","meanings":["Scottish or English: variant of   Lynn  ."]}]},{"name":"Roland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roland De Lynn was born in 1292, in Kilwinning, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Walter De Lynn, was 23 and his mother, Margaret, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Lynn."},"et":{"1292–":"1292–Surnud","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1302":"1302","1350":"1350","1